{"product_id": "201870", "page": 17, "page_order": 0, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-08-14", "text": "AC: R is a decent and good looking game but it is too similar to its previous AC2 and AC: B instalment and feels very repetitive if compared to previous chapters.\nOverall it is a good game that introduces some new solutions to the established gameplay and extends the world of AC series, but it feels extremely repetitive and doesn't really bring anything that players can feel excited about\nOverall: 60/100", "hours": 20.4, "username": "Zest Riddler", "products": 1247, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "201870", "page": 17, "page_order": 1, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-08-13", "text": "Assassin's Creed Revelations is definitely a good game and worth to play through, especially if one is interested in the Assassin's Creed story in general (like me). For me it was mostly fun. There was a very small amount of frustrating missions, but the overall gameplay fun was as known from the previous parts, only slightly improved here and there.\nThe map and the locations are wonderfully detailed and very enjoyable as usual, but the buildings to climb in freeroam are not as fun and versatile as known from AC 2 and Brotherhood. There are parcour levels like in the prequels, but not as many and they are rather linear (not bad, but not as big and challenging as in the prequels). As usual, there is much to do in freeroam like refurbishing shops, before they can be used, buying points of interest, capturing areas, training assassins and more. The story and the characters are well designed and left good memories behind.\nIt's not so much about the present storyline unfortunately, mostly about Ezio's time in Constantinople and you also get to play Altair in Masyaf a few times. It is not necessary that you have played AC 1, but if you did or at least know the story it's more fun, because you can relate and connect the stories to each other. DO PLAY AC 2 AND Brotherhood before, though. They are both bigger and have things I missed in Revelations (like these puzzle minigames, more secrets, present story, gorgeous parcour levels, ...). If you don't like them, don't try Revelations.\nThere are also some very abstract puzzle-platform levels for Desmond and, if you own the Lost Archive DLC, for Subject 16 (these levels are completely optional and do not integrate into Ezio's gameplay). They are quite challenging at some points and tell you about Desmond's live before AC 1 and about Subject 16's live. These are recommendable if you like experimental or indie puzzle platformers or if you are interested in the story. I recommend you playing AC 1 before, though, for the story.", "hours": 44.5, "username": "Firzen", "products": 215, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "201870", "page": 17, "page_order": 2, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-08-12", "text": "The game didnt Change much.  But the story is Amazing.  And Ezio had changes - Voice, Look etc. They did put Some efort to the character.", "hours": 33.9, "user_id": "76561198343987044", "username": "R@inby", "products": 39, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "201870", "page": 17, "page_order": 3, "recommended": false, "date": "2017-08-10", "text": "This is the first Assassin's Creed game I couldn't finish. It wasn't frustrating as much as it was just boring. It felt lazy, made without passion or attention to details. The characters don't look like themselves; it's not that they look older, they look like completely different people. The battle/defense sequences were annoying and unnecessary. The world didn't feel nearly as alive or as vast as the previous games. The story failed to hook me. Ezio storyline should've ended with Brotherhood. Last but not least, the game crashed on me regularly. Not worth it.", "hours": 32.5, "username": "RadioactiveJade", "products": 327, "early_access": false}
