{"product_id": "201870", "page": 17, "page_order": 8, "recommended": false, "date": "2017-08-03", "text": "In my opinion, this game was a big step backwards from Brotherhood. Sure they added bombs that you can throw but the millions of \"treasure chests\" carelessly placed through the map are mainly just bomb ingredients now and are thus no longer as fun to search and explore for.\nThe addition of the hook was more gimmicky than anything else. It can marginally speed certain things up like climbing but it slows me down more often than not and can also get you into trouble since you can no longer sprint and bump into guards (you use the hook to go over them which triggers an alert amongst all guards in the vicinity)\nThe posters are gone now and simply paying to refurbish buildings (armorer, tailor etc) creates notoriety which makes it significantly more frustrating and time consuming to \"buy everything\" if you are the collector type that has to complete everything to 100%. In other words, when building up notoriety it is painstakingly more challenging to bring it back down again. To make matters worse, when you get the notoriety to a high enough level the Templars attack one of your \"dens\" which leads to this absolutely awful mini-game where you motionlessly stand on a rooftop and direct a battle in the streets.\nThe combat is still as fun as Brotherhood however the addition of occasional slow-mo kills slows things down. The one improvement though is that you can choose what your sidearm is so you can use the smaller daggers with a pistol.\nEven the story seemed less interesting and the maps slightly smaller. I just found it tedious to push myself through this game but I finished it solely to move on to Assassin's Creed 3.", "hours": 12.5, "username": "acdcdave1387", "products": 260, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "201870", "page": 17, "page_order": 9, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-08-01", "text": "Fourth AC, and my fourth AC game as well, since I am going through them chronologically. Even though there is definitely stuff I prefer in one of the previous games here and there, Revelations is my favorite so far.\nConstantinopolis is my favorite city, you can move around it better thanks to the hookblade, the game looks better graphically and old Ezio is now all wise and stuff.\nIn addition to the main big city you get to visit Masyaf (the Assassin HQ from AC1) both as an old Ezio while it's in disrepair, and in couple of the missions you'll get to play as Altair around the time of Ac1 ending and what followed, including one where you are 80+ years old. Those are fun.\nOther than a tower defense style minigame (which you can avoid past the tutorial) it's an AssCreed all right, if you played AC2 or AC:B you'll feel right at home, and if you disliked them, Revelations will hardly win you over.", "hours": 17.4, "username": "slothicus", "products": 3846, "found_funny": 1, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "201870", "page": 18, "page_order": 0, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-08-01", "text": "i liked this game as i liked all the assassins creed games", "hours": 30.4, "username": "StarFoxx  The DevisionMaster", "products": 51, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "201870", "page": 18, "page_order": 1, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-07-31", "text": "An amazing ending for an amazing assassin.\nIn terms of gameplay, though I never was a fan of the franchise's combat, it did not ruin my experience and I loved the parkour.\nConstantinople is a stunning setting full of culture and history.\nThe city truly feels alive.", "hours": 13.9, "username": "Lefter", "products": 54, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "201870", "page": 18, "page_order": 2, "recommended": false, "date": "2017-07-31", "text": "wanna run around and kill defensless people then forget that happend cause its all a dream go ahead and play this game would you like to do the same thing everytime you log into it??? if so this games for you", "hours": 14.4, "username": "Impulse", "products": 76, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "201870", "page": 18, "page_order": 3, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-07-30", "text": "Just overall this was a better experience than brotherhood:\n* Good story content across all the key characters: Alta\u00efr, Erzio and Desmond.\n* Overall alot less mission spam on the map, game progressed more smoothly.\n* Faster climbing and movement across city *Yay*\n* Secondary weapon binding really was useful", "hours": 17.6, "username": "General Kysieran", "products": 420, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "201870", "page": 18, "page_order": 4, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-07-26", "text": "July 26th, 2017.\nDelete systemdetection.dll in your game folder if your graphics are going crazy (artifacts, screen tearing, etc.)\nIf you played Brotherhood then go ahead and grab this on sale. If you're new to the franchise and trying to figure out your play order then my words of wisdom are to play 1-3 if you like a convoluted story with uncharasmatic characters and hints of an alien conspiracy. Start with 4 if you dislike Desmond Miles, running through cities, and enjoy the pirate life.\nMy major issue with this game is that it was just a rebranded version of the 2 before it. 40+ hours between the Ezio games and you either don't know enough about the characters to engage with them or the few things you do discover feel like bad exposition or a plot device. Remember in 2 when Ezio's family was executed? You'll actually be hoping for more of those moments.\nThis game was worth the price on sale and the time spent on it. I did not go for 100% completion because there are other games to play and dragons to slay. I would not say it holds up as stand alone title as you really do need to be aware of where the story is at in the continuity of titles.\nI do have to say though, it was nice to have closure for the Altair character even though I feel like some more information about his lineage would have been gratifying. It's almost like they left out just enough of Altair's life to make a decent movie with but then the film studio said, \"naaaah, let's get Magneto on a twirling arm thing\". Unrelated I know, but I feel like it illustrates the missed opportunities of this franchise as a whole.\nRequiescat in Pace, Altair", "hours": 13.6, "user_id": "76561197966643420", "username": "J03Y.N0.CH1LL", "products": 208, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "201870", "page": 18, "page_order": 5, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-07-22", "text": "love it best assassins creed ever made", "hours": 16.9, "user_id": "76561198173669529", "username": "Mushtario", "products": 72, "found_funny": 1, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "201870", "page": 18, "page_order": 6, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-07-21", "text": "A great finale to the Ezio trilogy and conclusion of Altair's story. A bit repetitive and didn't bring much new to the table, but I'm always up for another Ezio story. 8.5/10.", "hours": 13.3, "username": "gamernes9", "products": 257, "early_access": false}
