{"product_id": "201870", "page": 22, "page_order": 9, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-06-27", "text": "Now this is weird\nThis game is Brotherhood in a new setting.\nThe content that was added was meh, at best.\nBombs ? Never used them much.\nDen defense? \u2665\u2665\u2665\u2665ing annoying.\nThis game is basicly AC: Brotherhood in Constantinople.\nI wish there was a neutral recommendation.", "hours": 0.7, "compensation": "Product received for free", "username": "mecoolGAMER", "products": 325, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "201870", "page": 23, "page_order": 0, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-06-26", "text": "This was my favorite AC game out of I thru III. The mechanics of the Ezio games were finally perfected with the hookblade and the bomb crafting made combat interesting also. Getting money is a bit harder in this game, but if you invest in shops and treasure maps early on, it's okay.\nThe best part of this game was the story, which is an element Ubisoft has neglected in later installments of this franchise. Ezio's character development over his 3 games trumps any other AC protagonist yet. Altair's chapters give him a lot more depth than the initial AC I story did also.\nThe graphics are good, the map is easy to get around, and the game is quite enjoyable all around.", "hours": 16.2, "username": "THE SCREW OF DAMNATION", "products": 87, "found_funny": 1, "early_access": false}
