{"product_id": "201870", "page": 46, "page_order": 6, "recommended": true, "date": "2016-08-25", "text": "It s good end story for the best assassin Ezio Auditore", "hours": 16.8, "user_id": "76561198030030425", "username": "\u017d\u010c\u010c\u017d\u017d\u017d\u010c\u010c\u0160\u017d\u017d\u010c\u010c\u017d\u010c", "products": 184, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "201870", "page": 46, "page_order": 7, "recommended": true, "date": "2016-08-22", "text": "This game would be worth it simply for its unique setting, and how beautifully it is realized. Constantinople and Byzantine history are personal favorites of mine, so being able to explore the city as it was at the turn of the 16th century is a real treat. Completing Ezio and Altair's stories was a poignent and satisfying experience that began with the original Assassin's Creed years prior. The Desmond stuff is tolerable, like usual, but not obnoxious or particularly in the way, not like usual. If you played AC2, and maybe Brotherhood, and then lost steam for the franchise, go ahead and finish Ezio's story with Revelations. It's a great ending. I wish I could say the same for Desmond's story concluion in AC3, but that's a review for another game!", "hours": 38.6, "user_id": "76561197995270012", "username": "Captain Kail", "products": 215, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "201870", "page": 46, "page_order": 8, "recommended": true, "date": "2016-08-19", "text": "The magical city of Costantinopoli is the center stage Revelations, the last chapter of Ezio's trilogy. Another great historical adventure by Ubisoft.", "hours": 9.8, "username": "S T A R B O Y", "products": 74, "early_access": false}
