{"product_id": "201870", "page": 67, "page_order": 2, "recommended": true, "date": "2015-12-31", "text": "Not as good as Brotherhood, but still a great game nonetheless.  There are some pretty cool additions like creating your own bombs, zip-lining, the hookblade adds a cooler element of parkour, and the rpg element of building up your brotherhood.  I also love how the story ties in the altair story (from the first assassin's creed) as well, explaining how his life lived out, a very unique aspect I have not seen in any other game.  It's one of the better assassin's creed games out there-definitely worth a play.", "hours": 62.5, "user_id": "76561198114776608", "username": "buckman333", "products": 23, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "201870", "page": 67, "page_order": 3, "recommended": true, "date": "2015-12-30", "text": "Very cool setting and story, but there are too many new features! - too many? Yep too many.\nThere's so much to do that you just cannot do everything. Because after the story there is no way to play along with Ezio anymore.\n\nI kind of like the idea of the dens and their defence but in the entire story - 24 hours - I only had to do this two or three times. I think that's because I always stayed anonymous or so but this is a fragile concept! If I want to defend my dens I have to be noticed by the guards but for every other situation it is bad to not be anonymous.\nOf course I still recommend because its story sets an interesting end to Ezios life as an assassin. Graphics are solid, too, and I like the voices. Both, in English and German.\nJaker", "hours": 25.0, "username": "jaker", "products": 62, "early_access": false}
