{"product_id": "201870", "page": 72, "page_order": 9, "recommended": true, "date": "2015-11-12", "text": "Hardly any improvement over the previous games. The awesome parkour and climbing mechanics are still there, and so is the horrible combat system. Controls are still a bit clunky (i.e. shift picks up a body instead of climbing down, daaaamn).\nWhat's new and sucks:\nWhat's new and good:", "hours": 25.1, "user_id": "76561198007688772", "username": "Aargh", "products": 778, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "201870", "page": 73, "page_order": 0, "recommended": true, "date": "2015-11-10", "text": "Without a doubt one of the best games I have ever played, the game takes you to Istanbul just shortly after the ottomans came to power, the city is beautiful and the devs made a serious attempt to make it historically correct, adding many landmarks that can still be seen today and make the city recongnizable.", "hours": 65.9, "username": "Artemis", "products": 36, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "201870", "page": 73, "page_order": 1, "recommended": true, "date": "2015-11-10", "text": "Maybe the best installment in the AC series, this game guarantees hours of fun. Although the game mechanics haven't changed that much, it still feels way smoother than in AC: Brotherhood. Also, the graphics have been given a major boost. However, it is the storyline that really sets this game apart, as well as the amiable characters.", "hours": 15.1, "user_id": "76561198057618922", "username": "Sir Lagsalot", "products": 71, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "201870", "page": 73, "page_order": 2, "recommended": true, "date": "2015-11-09", "text": "Best game in Ezio trilogy. Maybe city of Constantinople is not as atmospheric as renaissance Italy, but more polished gameplay make it actually more enjoyable. Plus game give interesting peek into Alta\u00efr's story. Must play for anybody who like ACII and Brotherhood.", "hours": 26.0, "username": "The Truth", "products": 526, "found_funny": 1, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "201870", "page": 73, "page_order": 3, "recommended": false, "date": "2015-11-08", "text": "All the previous Assassin's Creed games have been really good, but not this game. This game is when they got lazy. Poor animations, bugs all over the place and the game runs horribly.\nDon't buy this game.", "hours": 1.0, "username": "WE WUZ KANGZ", "products": 546, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "201870", "page": 73, "page_order": 4, "recommended": true, "date": "2015-11-08", "text": "It's just a redirect to uplay, but I'm okay with that... kinda", "hours": 2.0, "username": "Gon3r", "products": 132, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "201870", "page": 73, "page_order": 5, "recommended": true, "date": "2015-11-07", "text": "My first experience with an Assassin's Creed game came from watching a friend of mine play it on his XBox 360. He'd finished the story so I didn't get what had happened. That was Brotherhood. Needless to say he never let me play it.\nSteam sale rolls around some years ago, Brotherhood and ACII are discounted so I get them both. ACII was the closest to the first AC and I loved it's story. Brotherhood was the game I never got to play myself, and I enjoyed it but the story wasn't as hooking as 2's. I couldn't decide if I wanted to continue it.\nI'm glad I did. Revelations takes the story of ACII, the combat and gameplay of Brotherhood, mixes in the sense that you can only get from a favorite TV show or movie series that this is the end of your favorite character's story, and sets it to cook until well-done. A lot of the reviews I saw for this game only focus on what it was missing so they were lower scored. I'm gonna tell you what I got from this game, and you can decide if you'll enjoy it.\nIf you enjoyed ACII's story and Brotherhood's gameplay, you're getting both with this game. There's not much in terms of new things because it doesn't need those things. Revelations' boasts a wonderfully crafted story that at the end will leave you crying(yes, I cried.), the music helps with it's somber lows and action-paced highs(the main menu's looping music had me fighting tears with the vocals), the gameplay has just enough new mixed with old to keep you glued to the controller(or keyboard), and it's cast is at it's finest.\nSo any Ezio fans, do yourselves a favor and get this game. If you don't want to play it, look it up on Youtube to discover the end of the Auditore trilogy. But watching won't be the same as playing it.", "hours": 30.9, "user_id": "76561198035734604", "username": "The Daft Wolsker", "products": 122, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "201870", "page": 73, "page_order": 6, "recommended": true, "date": "2015-11-07", "text": "Thank you for your time reading this review that I made. And I would highly appreciate it if you can rate it to your liking. Below are the links for my other reviews that would complete this story arc.\nAssassin's Creed II -\nAssassin's Creed: Brotherhood -", "hours": 25.9, "username": "Like[A]SiR", "products": 1509, "found_funny": 9, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "201870", "page": 73, "page_order": 7, "recommended": true, "date": "2015-11-06", "text": "it's italian guy and the crystal skull", "hours": 19.9, "user_id": "76561198093177302", "username": "Amfibiman", "products": 111, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "201870", "page": 73, "page_order": 8, "recommended": true, "date": "2015-11-06", "text": "Great way to end the Ezio-based part of the series. The game was quite different from II and Brotherhood in that you go from Italy to Constantinople. It in a way feels like a revamped Assassins' Creed I. If you haven't played and Assassins' Creed games prior to this, I suggest you start with I or II and work your way forward. II, Brotherhood, and Revalations telling the story of Ezio Auditore is phenomenal. I have heard that the game series starts going downhill after this game. I have not played them yet, but it would be pretty hard to beat the past three games in my opinion. Anyway, this is one of the best series in gaming, hands down; a must have.", "hours": 23.8, "user_id": "76561198132716565", "username": "Pine_Straw", "products": 59, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "201870", "page": 73, "page_order": 9, "recommended": true, "date": "2015-11-05", "text": "Despite adding a number of features, Assassin's Creed Revelations is very similar to its predecessors, and that's both its biggest strength and weakness. There's nothing wrong with Assassin's Creed. It's a great franchise with unique, compelling and well-designed gameplay. The catch is that we've effectively been doing similar things for the last several years now. Incremental upgrades are more than welcome, but at some point players need a new experience.\nThat said, Revelations serves its lead characters well and is a very effective bookend. The improvements in graphics and storytelling, combined with already-great voice acting and music, help make this a memorable finale for some of the most interesting video game characters I've seen.\nIf you've been following the lives of Altair and Ezio this long, you owe it to yourself to see their last adventure.", "hours": 11.2, "username": "ZS-KEV", "products": 168, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "201870", "page": 74, "page_order": 0, "recommended": true, "date": "2015-11-03", "text": "Awesome", "hours": 58.6, "username": "Baphomet", "products": 328, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "201870", "page": 74, "page_order": 1, "recommended": true, "date": "2015-11-01", "text": "Have you ever been to Istanbul? What about Kostantiniyye of the 16th Century with all the Ottoman splendor and intrigue.", "hours": 71.3, "username": "cruist22", "products": 162, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "201870", "page": 74, "page_order": 2, "recommended": true, "date": "2015-11-01", "text": "WARNING: If you see reviews telling you UPlay is annoying, or horrible, or that it sucks the life out of everything, believe them.\nAs for Assassin's Creed: Revelations, if I could get UPlay to connect and let me on at least once, I would know what the game is actually like. However, since I can't even get the game to play (the 4.4 hours it says I have on the game are the hours I spent trying to get past UPlay's login screen), I can't give it a positive review. I had no idea if it's as fun as others claim, because after paying for my game on Steam, I have to log in to UPlay for who knows what reason. And unfortanately for me, UPlay has no idea what an internet connection is. I looked up what other people did about this problem (and lots of people have this problem), tried various fixes, but ultimately was denied access. Opening ports, rebooting my computer in safe mode, closing all other applications... nothing worked. If I can fix it in the future, after my frustration has died down and I reinstall the game, I will likely change my review to a positive one. Until then, remember that UPlay is horrible.\nEDIT: A friend recommened I use my iPhone's hotspot to login to UPlay, and it worked! I have finally been able to start playing the game. If you haven't been able to get through UPlay, try using a hotspot. I hope this helps someone!", "hours": 4.1, "user_id": "76561198066837793", "username": "WhereDidTheRumGo", "products": 85, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "201870", "page": 74, "page_order": 3, "recommended": false, "date": "2015-11-01", "text": "2 and Brotherhood were great.  This just felt like an unnecessary add on to score some $.  Couldn't have been much more disappointed with this one, killed the series for me.  Story was dull, left too many strings untied, city design was cramped and unintuitive, gameplay additions from brotherhood were not enough to merit another game.", "hours": 24.1, "username": "Halen5", "products": 951, "early_access": false}
